Introduction to IP Address:

1. There has to be way to identify where the request should go. IP address is essentially identity layer of networking.
Without an unique identifier packets would have no destination.

2. Some are designed for communication inside private network while others exposed services to the public internet. This distinction
becomes crucial.

3.Internet has evolved from IPV4 to IPV6. As billions of devices came online, the original address space become inefficient, forcing
the industry to rethink how global addressing works. 

4. When you design distributed system, IP address stop being a networking detail and become foundational building block.Every request,
service call and every connection ultimately depends on systems being able to find each other.


IPV4
-> IPV4 (Internet protocol version 4) is the most widely used addressing system. 32 bit address format. total address
available = 4.3 billion.  Uses : Tradiotional networking, web servers, and most current internet devices. challenges:
limited IPs, fragmentation and security concerns.

-> when users access your application, networking infrastructure uses IP addresses to determine where traffic should go 
and how should resposne return.

->internet eventually outgrew the assumptions on which IPv4 was built.

Ipv6

-> Ipv6 (Internet protocol version 6) next generation IP standard.

->128 - bit address format.Total address available = 340 undecillion (virtually unlimited)

-> Uses : IoT, mobile networks and future scalability.key benefits : large address space, better security,
improved routing efficiency. ipv6 is long term scalability.

Feature                      Ipv4                               Ipv6
Address size                  32 bit                            128 bit
Address format                decimal                           hexadecimal
Address space                 4.3 billion address               unlimited
Secuity                      relies on additional protocols     built in security
performance                  limited due to NAT & fragmentation   more efficient routing and handling
Adoption                     still widely used                   slowly being adopted

 -> Most production systems are deliberately designed so that the majority of the infrastructure remains hidden behind
the private networks. 

Public Ips
-> Assigned by Internet service provider (ISPs). Used to communicate over the internet. unique worldwide.

private Ips
 -> Used within local networks. cannot be accessed directly from the internet.
databases, caches, internal API's and backend services can communicate freely using private addresses. The public entry points
are load balancers, API gateways and reverse proxies.

-> A user reaches the public endpoint, but the request often travel through multiple layers of private infrastructure.
before reaching the service that actually processes the request.
-> public Ips provide reachability while private Ips provide isolation. Modern architecture rely on both to access scalaibility,
accessibility and security.

Why do we need private Ips?
-> Conserves public Ip address.
-> Enhances security (private Ips are not routable over the internet).
-> Enables Network Address Translation (NAT) to allow multiple devices to share a single public Ip.
-> Common in corporate networks, data centers and cloud environments.




















